I looked in the source code and the `e_goa_client_initable_init()` calls `goa_object_manager_client_new_for_bus_sync()` and assigns the returned object to a private property. I verified it is freed as it should on all places.

Looking deeper, the second question marks in the valgrind backtrace, from inside the add_interfaces(), calls `goa_object_manager_client_get_proxy_type()` from `src/goa/goa-generated.c:26666` and that generated code does have the `GHashTable` as a global memory, which is never freed:
```
26664	GType
26665	goa_object_manager_client_get_proxy_type (GDBusObjectManagerClient *manager G_GNUC_UNUSED, const gchar *object_path G_GNUC_UNUSED, const gchar *interface_name, gpointer user_data G_GNUC_UNUSED)
26666	{
26667	  static gsize once_init_value = 0;
26668	  static GHashTable *lookup_hash;
26669	  GType ret;
26670	
(gdb) 
26671	  if (interface_name == NULL)
26672	    return GOA_TYPE_OBJECT_PROXY;
26673	  if (g_once_init_enter (&once_init_value))
26674	    {
26675	      lookup_hash = g_hash_table_new (g_str_hash, g_str_equal);
26676	      g_hash_table_insert (lookup_hash, (gpointer) "org.gnome.OnlineAccounts.Account", (gpointer) (guintptr) (GOA_TYPE_ACCOUNT_PROXY));
...
```
it has a lot of interfaces. As it's a `goa` code, generated inside [the goa sources](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gnome-online-accounts/-/blob/249aed29a93df416927170d7ed95a6c652d08a96/src/goa/meson.build#L46), but not really a GOA thing, because it's generated by the `gdbus-codegen`. Any object manager will suffer of this.

Nonetheless, even technically a memory leak, I do not consider it harmful. The memory does not grow at all, it's filled once and then stay as such, helping to make things fast, not slow.

I'm closing this.

Thanks for the patch. Apart of the coding style, I think it's not okay to initialize gtk+ in a library. It's a duty of the application, not of the library.

In such case, would it make sense to use `gtk_is_initialized` function instead?

There would be good to have some debugging for it too, to help to aid any problems, thus maybe something like:
```c
   if (!gtk_is_initialized ()) {
      e_source_registry_debug_print ("%s: gtk+ is not initialized, skipping\n", G_STRFUNC);
      return;
   }
```

and possibly do it for both gtk3 and gtk4, to avoid differences in the library code.

The tricky part might be with the `e-credentials-prompter-impl-password.c`, where the `_libedataserverui_init_icon_theme()` is called in the `class_init` function, which might or might not be too early. It needs testing. As the `_libedataserverui_init_icon_theme()` can be called multiple times, then, if needed, a move to the object's `init()`, from the `class_init()` function, could work too.
